TY  - JOUR
AU  - Guo, Haifeng
AU  - Kontonikas, Alexandros
AU  - Maio, Paulo
T1  - Monetary Policy and Corporate Bond Returns
PY  - 2020
Y1  - 2020/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/rapstu/raaa005
JO  - The Review of Asset Pricing Studies
JA  - Rev Asset Pric Stud
VL  - 10
IS  - 3
SP  - 441
EP  - 489
SN  - 2045-9920
AB  - We investigate the impact of monetary policy shocks on excess corporate bonds returns. We obtain a significant negative response of bond returns to policy shocks, which is especially strong among low-grading bonds. The largest portion of this response is related to higher expected bond returns (risk premium news), while the impact on expectations of future interest rates (interest rate news) plays a secondary role. However, the interest rate channel is dominant among high-grading bonds and Treasury bonds. Looking at the two components of bond premium news, we find that the dominant channel for high-rating (low-rating) bonds is term premium (credit premium) news. (JEL 44, E52, G10, G12)Received: March 25, 2019: Editorial decision: March 27, 2020 by Editor: Hui Chen. Authors have furnished an Internet Appendix, which is available on the Oxford University Press Web site next to the link to the final published paper online.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rapstu/raaa005
